english:
  title: Memorial Petition for Bestowing Rank Upon My Father
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant is of humble talent and offers scant contribution, yet I have undeservedly received Your Majesty's grace and been granted the title of meritorious subject. Moreover, you have graciously permitted that rank be conferred upon my parents and wife—such beneficence knows no bounds. Yet the conferring of rank upon fathers, save in cases of posthumous honor, remains incomplete in practice. Does not the sovereign's grace extend even to the realm of shadows and spirits? How then should it alone be withheld from those yet living?

    Your Highness previously granted rank to the father of Heemin, and now to the father of Sekmyeong. This is surely because it proves difficult to fulfill all at once, and so you proceed by degrees, thereby realizing the sacred will to ennoble fathers. My father, whose years have not yet advanced far, awaits his turn in hope that the moment of grace will surely come. I should wait with patience.

    Yet my father, the official Hee, now stands at eighty-three years of age. Like the sun sinking toward the western hills, each dawn and dusk brings no guarantee. This is why I urgently seek that he receive this honor while yet he lives, why I pour forth these words with such haste, despite risking offense to the throne. I cannot contain myself.

    It is true that only meritorious subjects receive enfeoffment—this is the established law of the realm. Yet conferring rank upon the fathers of such subjects is also Your Highness's own decree. Few fathers of meritorious subjects remain living. To enfeoff these few would confirm your word, and how could any outsider dare cite this precedent to violate the established constitution?

    Since the age of Yu and Xia, there has existed the practice of honoring the state's elders. That King Wen and King Wu established Zhou came about through their devotion to this principle. Thus all sovereigns since ancient times have revered the national elder. When our late king founded the realm, following this way of virtue, recognizing that my father was both aged and of long standing, he appointed him Inspector of the Crown Prince's Attendants, and soon after elevated him to Prince of the Mansion of Officials. Yet the previous king, noting he was no meritorious subject, revoked his title, instead conferring retirement status upon him, and granted him annual stipend and salary—all expressions of honoring his advanced years.

    Recently the Censorate submitted a memorial requesting suspension of his stipend, yet this was not due to any fault. However, among the elders of the present court, none surpasses my father in years. If rank were conferred simply because his age exceeds eighty and he is the eldest in the realm, thereby demonstrating the state's respect for the aged, what objection could there be? Even should this become precedent, how many will reach such years? Thus my father too may rightfully receive enfeoffment.

    Moreover, though my humble person now holds my post and also bears the title of an enfeoffed lord, my father has lost his rank and stipend. Though I receive favor and honor, how can my heart rest easy? To surrender my title and have it granted to my father—this is my deepest wish.

    What son does not desire to see honor and eminence bestowed upon his living father? Yet few achieve this fortune, which is why the practice of posthumous honor exists. Yet this too is a sorrow. I and my father have been permitted to participate in the covenant of kinship, and to receive Your Highness's grace regarding the enfeoffment of fathers—such beneficence is boundless. Yet my father has not yet received this command. Should he depart from this prosperous reign in a single day, the pain of my lifelong misfortune would know no measure. What comfort would even posthumous honor bring to my heart? This is why day and night I rise on tiptoes, watching and hoping for this grace to descend.

    Your Highness has made covenant with us through solemn oath to secure trust for ten thousand generations. The conferral of rank upon parents is inscribed in your royal decree. I humbly beseech Your Highness to enact this ceremony, thereby demonstrating your faith, illuminating the governance of filial piety. Then my father and I, moved by such grace, will swear that our devotion to repay this kindness shall remain steadfast and pure until we crumble to dust, unwavering in our reverence.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Heemin and Sekmyeong are references to previously honored meritorious subjects whose fathers received posthumous or delayed rank.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'covenant through solemn oath' refers to the bond established between the king and his meritorious officials.
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase 'the sun sinking toward the western hills' is a classical metaphor for approaching death or the end of one's years.
